Bright- clear- wind 0-5 mph NE.  Surface temp 68 F.  Lily pads and water shield surfacing.
Slightly hazy- wind ~ 5mph NE.  Surface water temp 76 F.
Bright- clear- calm.  Surface water temp 80 F.
Surface Water Temp  -  79 deg F.  Bright- clear- wind 0-5 mph NNE.
Surface water temp  -  74 deg F.  Bright- clear- calm.  Water relatively clear- but with slight green algal tint.

Hazy sun to light overcast.  Wind 0-5 var.  Surface water temp. 75 F.  The Secchi depth reading remains lower than normal- but the green algal tint is gone and has bveen replaced by a gray/brown tint which is likely a high plankton population.

Bright- clear- calm.  Surface water temp  -  down to 64 deg F.  The gray/brown tint noted last month continues and the Secchi depth has not improved as it normally does later in the year.  It is perhaps wise to note that water level is EXTREMELY low ... approximately 7 feet down from just several years ago.  The lake is a seepage lake and many in this area are suffering the same fate.

Bright with light overcast- calm.  Surface water temp  -  54 deg F.  The gray/brown tint previously reported has persisted and the Secchi depth has not recovered as it usually does in the fall.  DNR sources also feel that the gray/brown is likely due to plankton.  The Secchi reading recorded is that lowest that I have seen since I have been on this site.  Lake level is still the lowest since the mid 80's according to local sources.
Surface temp 65 F- bright- clear.  Winds light to calm.
Bright- clear- wind 5-10 NW.  Surface temp 74 F.
Clear and sunny- wind 0-5 west- surface temp 79 F.
Bright and clear.  Wind calm.  Surface temp 80 F.
Skies bright- but hazy.  Wind 0-5 easterly.  Surface temp 69 F.
Clear and bright- wind 0-5 westerly- surface temp 57 F.

Clear and bright- wind calm.  Surface temp 53 F.  The sudden decrease in Secchi depth noted probably relates to low water.  This small (23 acre) lake has lost approx. half of its water volume and 6.5 feet in depth over the last 5-6 years.  The color of the turbidity is gray-brown and suggests plankton.  It is definitely not the green of an algae bloom.  Note: high capacity well nearby.
Surface temp 56 F- clear and bright.  Wind 0-5 NW.  Slight brown turbidity.
Surface temp 68 F.  Bright and clear.  Wind 5 mph NW.  Slight brown turbidity.

Surface temp. 76 F.  Bright And clear.  Wind 0-5 mph W.  Green-brown turbidity.  Floating filamentous algae.
Surface temp 75 F.  Broken clouds.  Wind 0-5 W.  Brown turbidity.  Some filamentous algae.
Surface temp 80 F.  Bright and clear.  Wind 5 mph NE.  Brown turbidity.
Surface temp 73 F.  Hazy sun.  Wind 0-5 mph E.  Brown turbidity.
note: Drought has severly reduced lake level (8 1/2 feet since 2003).  Phosphorus level roughly doubled since 2003.  No identified external phosphorus source.  A concentration effect

Bright and clear- Surface Temp  69 deg F- Wind 5-10 SE.  The Secchi reading is anomalous when compare to the April reading.  A brouwn cloudiness beginning roughly 8 feet below the surface.

Bright and clear- Surface Temp  84 deg F- Wind 0-5 variable.  Lake looking clearer and healthier than earlier this season.

Hazy sun- wind  0-5 NW- surface temp - 76 deg F.  Again- no green tint- but slight particulate turbidity.  Heavy growth of large leaf pond weed around the lake perimeter.
Clear + sunny- wind - calm- surface temp - 63 deg F.  Previous particulate much diminished.  No green algal tint noted throughout the summer.
